Title: The Gift of the Magi
Credit: Written by
Author: O. Henry
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/21/2025
Notes: Period live-action; early 1900s New York; warm naturalistic light; shabby-genteel palette of browns, grays, and faded reds

===

INT. FURNISHED FLAT - DAY

A shabby little flat at eight dollars a week. Worn red carpet. A thin pier-glass between the windows. A letter-box and silent electric button belong to the vestibule below; on a card: "Mr. James Dillingham Young."

DELLA, about twenty, slender, in a simple worn dress, sits at a small table. Brown hair pinned up. She counts coins into a meager pile — mostly pennies.

NARRATOR
One dollar and eighty-seven cents. That was all. And sixty cents of it was in pennies. Pennies saved one and two at a time by bulldozing the grocer and the vegetable man and the butcher until one's cheeks burned. Three times Della counted it. And the next day would be Christmas.

She finishes the third count. The total does not change. She flops down on the shabby little couch and howls — full, helpless sobs.

NARRATOR
Life is made up of sobs, sniffles, and smiles, with sniffles predominating.

Della gradually subsides from sobs to sniffles. She dabs her cheeks with a powder rag, rises, and stands by the window.

Outside: a gray cat walks a gray fence in a gray backyard.

DELLA
(soft, to herself)
Tomorrow Christmas Day. And I have one dollar and eighty-seven cents for Jim.

She turns from the window. Her eyes find the pier-glass. She whirls, stands before it. Eyes shining; color draining from her face.

Rapidly she pulls down her hair and lets it fall to its full length — a cascade of brown waters reaching below her knee, almost a garment.

NARRATOR
There were two possessions of the James Dillingham Youngs in which they both took a mighty pride. One was Jim's gold watch that had been his father's and his grandfather's. The other was Della's hair. Had the queen of Sheba lived in the flat across the airshaft, Della would have let her hair hang out the window to dry just to depreciate Her Majesty's jewels. Had King Solomon been the janitor, Jim would have pulled out his watch every time he passed, just to see him pluck at his beard from envy.

Della does the hair up again, nervously, quickly. She falters. A tear or two splashes on the worn red carpet.

On goes her old brown jacket. On goes her old brown hat. With a whirl of skirts and the brilliant sparkle still in her eyes, she flutters out the door.

EXT. STREET - DAY

Della hurries along a modest city block, Christmas eve bustle around her, thin coat drawn close.

She stops under a sign: "Mme. Sofronie. Hair Goods of All Kinds."

INT. MME. SOFRONIE'S SHOP - DAY

One flight up. DELLA enters, panting, collects herself.

MADAME SOFRONIE stands behind the counter — large, too white, chilly, hardly looking the "Sofronie."

DELLA
Will you buy my hair?

MADAME SOFRONIE
I buy hair. Take yer hat off and let's have a sight at the looks of it.

Della removes the old brown hat. Down ripples the brown cascade.

Madame lifts the mass with a practised hand.

MADAME SOFRONIE
Twenty dollars.

DELLA
Give it to me quick.

Madame works with scissors and practised speed. The long hair is taken. Coins — twenty dollars — pass into Della's palm. Della's eyes are bright; she does not look back at the fallen length.

EXT. CITY STREETS / SHOP WINDOWS - DAY

The next two hours on rosy wings. DELLA ransacks stores — trays of watches, chains, trinkets — searching with fierce tenderness.

She finds it at last in a jeweler's case: a platinum fob chain, simple and chaste in design, value by substance alone.

NARRATOR
It surely had been made for Jim and no one else. Quietness and value — the description applied to both. It was even worthy of The Watch.

A CLERK takes twenty-one dollars. Della hurries away with the chain and eighty-seven cents.

INT. FURNISHED FLAT - LATE AFTERNOON

DELLA's intoxication gives way to prudence. She lights the gas, gets out curling irons, and works before the pier-glass — repairing the ravages made by generosity added to love.

Within forty minutes her head is covered with tiny, close-lying curls. She looks wonderfully like a truant schoolboy. She studies her reflection long, carefully, critically.

DELLA
If Jim doesn't kill me before he takes a second look at me, he'll say I look like a Coney Island chorus girl. But what could I do — oh! what could I do with a dollar and eighty-seven cents?

She sets the platinum fob chain carefully aside. At the stove: coffee made; a frying-pan on the back, hot and ready for chops.

INT. FURNISHED FLAT - EVENING

Seven o'clock. DELLA doubles the fob chain in her hand and sits on the corner of the table near the door Jim always enters.

A step on the stair, away down on the first flight. She turns white for a moment. She whispers a little silent prayer.

DELLA
Please God, make him think I am still pretty.

The door opens. JIM steps in and closes it — twenty-two, thin, very serious, needing a new overcoat, without gloves. He carries the quiet burden of twenty dollars a week.

He stops inside the door, immovable as a setter at the scent of quail. His eyes fix upon Della — an expression she cannot read. Not anger, nor surprise, nor disapproval, nor horror. He simply stares with that peculiar look.

Della wriggles off the table and goes for him.

DELLA
Jim, darling, don't look at me that way. I had my hair cut off and sold because I couldn't have lived through Christmas without giving you a present. It'll grow out again — you won't mind, will you? I just had to do it. My hair grows awfully fast. Say Merry Christmas! Jim, and let's be happy. You don't know what a nice — what a beautiful, nice gift I've got for you.

JIM
You've cut off your hair?

DELLA
Cut it off and sold it. Don't you like me just as well, anyhow? I'm me without my hair, ain't I?

Jim looks about the room curiously.

JIM
You say your hair is gone?

DELLA
You needn't look for it. It's sold, I tell you — sold and gone, too. It's Christmas Eve, boy. Be good to me, for it went for you. Maybe the hairs of my head were numbered, but nobody could ever count my love for you. Shall I put the chops on, Jim?

Out of his trance Jim wakes. He enfolds his Della.

NARRATOR
Eight dollars a week or a million a year — what is the difference? The magi brought valuable gifts, but that was not among them.

Jim draws a package from his overcoat pocket and throws it upon the table.

JIM
Don't make any mistake, Dell, about me. I don't think there's anything in the way of a haircut or a shave or a shampoo that could make me like my girl any less. But if you'll unwrap that package you may see why you had me going a while at first.

White fingers and nimble tear at string and paper. An ecstatic scream of joy — then a quick change to hysterical tears and wails. Jim holds her, comforting.

In the open package: The Combs — side and back — pure tortoise shell with jewelled rims, just the shade for the beautiful vanished hair.

NARRATOR
Beautiful combs Della had worshipped long in a Broadway window. Her heart had simply craved and yearned over them without the least hope of possession. And now they were hers, but the tresses that should have adorned them were gone.

She hugs the combs to her bosom. At length she looks up with dim eyes and a smile.

DELLA
My hair grows so fast, Jim!

Then she leaps up like a little singed cat.

DELLA
Oh, oh!

She holds out the platinum fob chain eagerly upon her open palm. The dull precious metal seems to flash with her bright spirit.

DELLA
Isn't it a dandy, Jim? I hunted all over town to find it. You'll have to look at the time a hundred times a day now. Give me your watch. I want to see how it looks on it.

Instead of obeying, Jim tumbles down on the couch, puts his hands under the back of his head, and smiles.

JIM
Dell, let's put our Christmas presents away and keep 'em a while. They're too nice to use just at present. I sold the watch to get the money to buy your combs. And now suppose you put the chops on.

They look at each other — two foolish, precious children in an eight-dollar flat — the chain in her hand, the combs against her breast, the watch gone, the hair gone.

NARRATOR
The magi, as you know, were wise men — wonderfully wise men — who brought gifts to the Babe in the manger. They invented the art of giving Christmas presents. And here I have lamely related to you the uneventful chronicle of two foolish children in a flat who most unwisely sacrificed for each other the greatest treasures of their house. But of all who give gifts these two were the wisest. Of all who give and receive gifts, such as they are wisest. Everywhere they are wisest. They are the magi.

Della moves to the stove. Jim watches her short curls in the gaslight. The chops begin to cook. Outside, the gray evening holds the city — Christmas Eve.

FADE OUT.

THE END
